    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Returns the real valued "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "-point inverse discrete Fourier transform\nof "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", where "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " contains the non-negative frequency terms of a\nHermitian-symmetric sequence. "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the length of the result, not the\ninput."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "If you specify an "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " such that "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " must be zero-padded or truncated, the\nextra/removed values will be added/removed at high frequencies. One can\nthus resample a series to "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "m"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " points via Fourier interpolation by:\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a_resamp = irfft(rfft(a), m)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The correct interpretation of the hermitian input depends on the length of\nthe original data, as given by "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". This is because each input shape could\ncorrespond to either an odd or even length signal. By default, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "irfft"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "\nassumes an even output length which puts the last entry at the Nyquist\nfrequency; aliasing with its symmetric counterpart. By Hermitian symmetry,\nthe value is thus treated as purely real. To avoid losing information, the\ncorrect length of the real input "
            },
            {
              "kind": "strong",
              "text": "must"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " be given."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
